column168: On January 16, 2019, at 1012 hours personnel in the CSXT Russell, KY yard reported an unknown odor.  Quick Response, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched and found the source of the odor was GATX 201128, a loaded tank car of Isoprene was leaking due a liquid valve not being fully closed and the secondary securement plug not tool tight.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Odfjell Terminals, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2019-0106-00032.  Quick Response was able to close the valve and properly secure the closure plug.  The issue’s identified and corrective actions were communicated to shipper’s representative: Darrell McCann.  The car was released for transportation.

column168: On January 9, 2019 at 0825 hrs. personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard Mechanical Shop, discovered SCMX4333 a loaded tank car of Ethyl Methyl Ketone, leaking from top of the car near the protective housing. The car was isolated in the Mechanical Shop and CHEMTREC, Shell Industries, Avon Fire Department, IDOT, NRC, US EPA,IDEM, were notified. CHEMTREC Report # 2019-0109-00067. SunPro a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid and vapor lines were open with the secondary closures less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Rick Ferguson (832) 712-9770. Contractor personnel closed both valves, secured the secondary fittings  and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 required.  Cause Code: 119, 136 NARRI: 5, 5

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND PEROXYACETIC ACID MIXTURES, STABILIZED WITH ACIDS, WATER, AND NOT MORE THAN 5 PERCENT PEROXYACETIC ACID
column168: At 1605 ET ERTS was contacted by XPO driver Kevin Eversgerd of XPO Logistics NTH about a cargo release. It was reported that due to the customer puncturing the cargo with a forklift during the delivery approximately 2 gallons of hazardous UN3149 OxiDate 2.0 Hydrogen Peroxide released on the customer's dock. The customer is Cleaver Brooks and they will complete the cleanup of the product themselves. No contractor is needed. Ellis Long of Cleaver Brooks confirmed they will handle the disposal as well. There were no soils, drains or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. Due to the products hazardous properties, a DOT 5800 report will be needed for this incident. ERTS will upload the SDS and BOL. No waste container ID will be needed.

column168: At 0648 ET, ERTS was notified by Nicholas Menzo of XPO (XPN) regarding a cargo release. According to the caller, approximately 1-cup of UN1263 "DURACOAT™ PRE-CATALYZED LACQUER FLAT 10 SHEEN 5 GAL; M614-24108" released to a trailer floor (319-5980) from (3) 5-gal. metal pails improper loading when cargo fell on top of the pails crushing them. The caller indicated the release was contained to the trailer floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined the release could be cleaned with a sweeper, absorbent material and PPE, and containerized into a (1) 20-gallon DM to be staged in OS&D. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. There is no regulatory reporting required for this release due to spills in trailers and contained areas not being reportable. There is a DOT 5800 required for this release due to its PG II classification. Waste container entry is provided below. SDS is uploaded to entry; status set to waste label provided. Chemtrec was notified and Phil issued report #20190114-00024.

column25: PINE ISLAND CHEMICAL SOLUTIONS NORTH LLC
column168: At 0719 ET, ERTS was notified by Bradley Weber of XPO (LSL) regarding a cargo release. According to the caller, approximately 275-gal. of "Aqucar DB 5 Microbiocide" released to a trailer floor (4414519) from a (1) 2,434-lb. poly tote due to forklift accident. The caller indicated the release was contained to the trailer floor and also the ground floor in the parking lot. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined the release will need a contractor dispatched to the location for a Tote spill clean up because the terminal personnel do not have the materials to clean up the spill. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. There is DOT5800 reporting due to the size of the container. The LA Department of Public Safety was notified and Marcus Roberts issued report # 19-00170. The Caddo Parish was notified for regulatory reporting purposes. No report # was issued. Chemtrec was notified at 0815 ET and Kevin issued report # 2019011400034 was issued. The LADEQ online report will be completed. ERTS will upload the BOL and SDS. USES was contacted for dispatch. All waste was containerized to 9-55gal poly drums and left on site for terminal to manage.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: January 9, 2019 at 1007 ET Wes Parker with XPO terminal XCF called ERTS regarding a 1 gallon release of winter pow-r diesel fuel treatment from a 55 gallon metal drum. The release impacted the trailer floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller who stated he felt capable and confident in cleaning and containing the release into a 95 gallon poly over pack. No soils, drains, or water ways were impacted by the release. No regulatory reporting will be conducted at this time. Waste container ID number was generated XCF - 053479. Chemtrec was called and  took the call issuing report number 2019010900105 . A DOT 5800 will be required due to its packing group being a PG ll.

column168: The NATX 252892 was discovered leaking from the manway due to five of eight bolts being less than tool tight as the car was being brought into PTRA American Yard on Wednesday morning as observed by TXDOT Inspector Michael Horton.  After reviewing the movement history of the car we found that it was spotted in Houston Fuel Oil Terminal on 1/1, moved within the plant a couple of times, then released back to the PTRA for spotting at a later date.  Per discussion with TXDOT, since HFOT accepted the car then released it back into transportation the responsibility to ensure the rail car is properly secured for movement falls upon HFOT. The PTRA called out Slick Response services to inspect and install a manway gasket, secure the manway to tool tight specifications and pressure wash the product from the exterior of the tank.
column169: I emailed the cause of the leak to the customer. TXDOT Inspector Horton has personally followed up with the customer to discuss the incident and why they are responsible for the leak.

On January 11, 2019 at approximately 1905 hours Brandon Boone, Parkersburg Utility Employee reported that in the Parkersburg WV yard, a strong smell of a chemical coming from a tank car. Sunpro a CSXT response contractor responded and found TILX 301522 leaking from the top of the tank car.  The tank car was isolated and the Shipper Kraton Polymers was notified, Sunpro responded and found the Sample line a quarter turn open and the secondary closure plug less than tool tight.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Kraton ( Jerri Sage PH# 904-349-1180). TILX 301522 was released back into transportation without any further delays. This did not require a special switch.

A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Systems, Inc was in route from the shipper’s location to the  intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a  single transport vehicle for continued transportation.  While using straps to secure the tote to the  enclosed cargo area, the top corner of the tote cracked, resulting in a spill. The material spilled was immediately contained in containment area directly under transport vehicle. Absorbent material was applied to the spilled material. The material was  transferred out of the damaged tote and into a new container. All absorbent and spill debris was  placed in the  drum and secured for shipment to the designated treatment facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or aging was observed. Once pressure was applied it was then evident we had a brittle tote.   Drivers will be retrained on container integrity and warehouse personnel will continue to inspect  each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions  should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity.  IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container  used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

column168: During the process of loading a vacuum tanker with PCB oil at the Veolia facility, a spill of approximately 5 gallons of PCB oil occurred. The PCB oil spilled from the scrubber at the vacuum pump.  The oil was being loaded from various  totes of oil.  The MP Environmental Services vacuum truck was decontaminated with kerosene and water and removed from the loading dock.  Spilled oil was removed from the loading dock containment are.  The loading dock containment surfaces were washed with kerosene fuel and rinsed with water.  A triple rinse was performed. A detergent compound was then used to remove the residual diesel fuel from the containment area. Wash rinse water and solid debris were collected for disposal as PCB contaminated materials.
column169: 1) Verify that capacity of the tanker and the amount of oil that will be pumped into the tanker, adjust for capacity as necessary by performing a tanker dome inspection.  2) Place an overflow bucket or other container under the vacuum pump scrubber outlet to catch any  oil and oil foam that may pass through.

It was reported that (1) 5 gallon  steel  pail of UN 1263 Value Works Utility Wash Thinner was found damaged due to a lack of dunnage. Approximately 1 gallon released to the floor of trailer # 3113321 . ERTS reviewed SDS with the caller, and caller expressed comfort in terminal personnel's ability to safely clean released product with absorbents and donning appropriate PPE. Terminal personnel placed impacted absorbents and damaged pail into a 10-gallon steel drum. There were no storm drains, soils, or waterways impacted by the released material. There is no further cleanup needed.

On January 23, 2019, at 1209 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal NWY notified ERTS of a UN3266 "Advantedge 400 Replenisher" release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched WEL to the site to conduct all cleanup and over packing operations. Contractors arrive onsite at 1420 ET, and confirmed 2-ounces released to the exterior of the container due to the closure cap in the top of the tote being loose. An absorbent pad with a citric acid solution to neutralize the tote was utilized to wipe down the tote. The contractor secured the cap and closed it securing it for continued shipment. The terminal indicated that they will try to ship this to the consignee tomorrow not that it is securely fastened. No waste was generated from this incident.

column168: 01/17/2019, at 1424 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier yard discovered SKSK101212, a loaded railcar of environmentally Liquid (Uses oil), leaking from the protective housing area. The car was isolated and Safety Kleene Systems INC New York State DEC and NRC were notified.  Clean Harbors emergency number was contacted with no report # provided. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the tank car was leaking from the protective housing area. Upon cutting the security seal and accessing the protective housing it was fond that the Vapor line valve was open and the secondary securement plug was uninstalled. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Scott Sullivan 781-792-5727. Contractor personnel closed the Vapor line valve, installed the secondary plug, removed all residual product from the outside of the railcar and conducted environmental remediation. The railcar was released to transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.
column169: (NAR cause code: 136 Vapor valve open plug not secured)

column168: On 1/3/2019, JBHU 260428 was reported leaking by a JB Hunt driver at BNSF San Bernardino IMF. The waybill lists that the unit was carrying hazardous material. Premium Environmental Service was contacted and subsequently dispatched Patriot Environmental to do remediation the load at the facility. The cause of the leak was a drum, at the nose of the container, being pressed up against the screws of the manifest box and about 15 gallons was spilled out of the drum. This has been deemed as shipper   s responsibility.  Cargo, parking space and haz pit was remediated by Patriot Environmental.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve
column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Tank car DOWX 4873 was reported to be releasing product from the bottom of the car.  Inspection of the car found the top-operated bottom outlet valve open approximately one-eighth of a turn, allowing product to push past the gasket (damaged) in the bottom outlet cap.  The valve was closed stopping the release.    Teflon packing material was added to the top housing to supplement the existing packing around the operating stem to prevent the valve from vibrating open.  In addition, a new cap gasket was installed in the bottom outlet cap.
column169: Ensure valves and gaskets are inspected and repaired/replaced prior to loading and release of cars.  (NAR:148, 580)

column168: On January 30, 2019, at 0217 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal NNA notified ERTS of a 4.5-gallon release of UN1263 UltraLaq® Water White Precatalyzed Lacquer from a 5-gallon metal pail to the trailer floor due to improper loading. ERTS determined terminal personnel could clean the release with the appropriate provide PPE. Terminal personnel donned PPE and placed the damaged drum and impacted absorbents into a 30-gallon metal drum which was staged onsite in the terminals waste area for terminal personnel to manage.

The tank car was reported to be leaking by UPRR Yard personnel. Manager of Hazardous Materials Tom Robinson was called to respond. Manager Robinson inspected the car and found the air valve plug not applied and the valve was opened. Manager Robinson closed the valve and properly secured the plug. The spillage was remediated and nothing was observed to hit the ground. The car was released back into transportation once properly secured.

column168: It was confirmed that due to a multiple vehicle accident, (4) 55- gallon poly drums containing UN3286, 3, 6.1, PGII were ejected fro the trailer, causing 200 gallons to spill onto a 75 yard x 30 yard area of the soil. The spill also impacted 72 foot x 65 yard area of the asphalt. Additionally,  a concrete culvert was also impacted with the released product. During clean up operations, it began to rain and free-standing puddles contaminated with the spilled was product formed as a result. A vacuum truck was utilized to suck up the contaminated puddles. Absorbent boom was placed into the culvert.  The contaminated soil was excavated and placed into 5 roll off boxes and fresh soil and hydro-seed was placed on the excavation areas. The concrete culvert was pressure-washed and an approximate 600-700 gallons of impacted water was removed  from the site in (4) 20 cubic-yard roll off boxes.

column168: There were 2 spills on this.  First the unloader said to hook his hose up and they would use their pump to unload.  They realized their pump shouldn't be used shortly in to it.  The second spill was at the end of the offload.  He was able to clear the line from the trailer to the pump but was having difficulty clearing the section from the pump to the customer tank.  When he disconnected another 6 ounces spilled on to the ground.
column169: The driver is new and failed to follow his training.  On the first spill he should have opened the bleeder valve that comes off the trailer external valve.  Then walk the lines several times to it draining off approximately 3-4 gallons which would create a big enough air pocket in the hose to safely disconnect from the highest connection point.  On the second spill he should have walked the lines to the 'petcocks' on the pump and again drained off 3-4 gallons before disconnecting from the highest point.  Driver was coached on both of these and is also being brought in to spend some time with the training team to ensure he has a good grasp on various unload situations.

column168: The driver arrived and checked his ticket that said "customer near empty". After that he began to fill the tank, while filling he heard an intermittent whistle. He waited and listened for the gurgling noise but that noise never came so he stopped and went up to the truck to see how much he had pumped, which was 150 gallons more than the 275 gallon tank could hold. No one was home so he called the owner who arrived a few minutes later and let him in. They went down into the basement where he saw the plug sitting on top of the tank, which is why the whistle did not work properly. The drain on the floor was plugged and the majority of the product ran out of the basement in a clay pipe which emptied on a hillside and ran into a ditch that contained the product until it was cleaned up. Within 2 hours an Environmental Response team was dispatched to the scene, the NRC was notified (1235774), the Ohio EPA was notified 1901-EPA-0096, and the Stark County LEPC was notified.
column169: In our spring safety meetings we will be emphasizing the importance of taking your time and being overly cautious when filling tanks. We want to make sure that the drivers know they can always stop the flow,check the meter, and then continue the flow again if they are unsure of how full the tank is. We will also be implementing a tank inspection program.

column168: The package(UN 4G fiberboard box) was prepared at the Corning Concord facility and shipped by ground freight on the afternoon of 1/8/2019. At the carriers distribution hub in Wilmington, NC, a freight handler notified his supervisor that the package was"smoking". The supervisor relocated the package to a remote location at the facility and phoned the Corning Wilmington facility(consignee) at-0600 on 1/9/2019. Coming Wilmington personnel responded to the call and went to the carriers facility. They inspected the package and noted that there was no smoking(or vapor) being released. They noted no wetness or liquid on the outside of the package. They packaged the box with vermiculite into a UN 1 H2 polypropylene drum, reproducing hazard marks and labels on the outside of the drum. The carrier then continued transport of the shipment to the destination, making Coming the first stop for the truck. At Corning Wilmington, the package was received and taken to a fume-hood where the box was opened and inspected(see photos 1-2) Observations upon examination of the box contents:  The plastic barrier bag containing the bottles was intact and contained liquid material. The bag was examined; there were no rips, tears, or damage. The tie-wrap securing the plastic barrier bag was intact. The Styrofoam inserts were deformed, appearing to have been chemically dissolved.  None of the bottles were broken. All four caps for the bottles were sheared(unevenly with a jagged break) across the top. The lower threads of the caps were still on the bottles, but the tops of the caps had separated from the bottles and were no longer affixed(see photos 3-4). Secondary closures(tape and paraffin wrap) were still intact on the bottles and held the lower segment of the bottle caps. Post-incident investigation: The barrier bag contained the liquid, such that the only possible route for the vapor to escape was through the neck of the bag secured by the zip-tie. Based on the amount of liquid remaining in the bag, it appeared that only a small amount of vapor had been released. Coming personnel replicated the cap shearing/failure that resembled the broken caps as found in the package by slightly over-tightening a cap by hand. We are not aware of any conditions that would have created a pressure significant enough to pop the tops off of the caps.
column169: • Test alternate cap/cap Iiner(insert) combinations for chemical compatibility(vendor sending alternates to be tested). • Obtain and use torque wrench for tightening caps on bottles to a specific level to avoid over-tightening(already on order). • Cease the use of Styrofoam packaging inserts for this material due to chemical incompatibility(effective immediately). • Order new, more robust packaging system that uses hydrostatically-tested metal cans as intermediate packaging and fiberboard separators(already ordered). Use barrier bag to contain bottle inside intermediate can. Devise alternative technique to close barrier bag securely, not allowing vapor to escape. • Update and supplement hazardous material transportation training and procedures for Coming employees based on findings and corrective actions from this incident • Cease shipment of this material until all corrective actions have been addressed and a resolution has been identified and implemented.

column168: On January 28, 2019 at 2015 EST, ERTS received a call from XPO Terminal UPH regarding a hazardous cargo release. It was reported that approximately 32-ounces of UN1824 Sodium hydroxide solution, 8, PGII (Memclean EXA 2) leaked from the cap of a 250-gallon plastic tote on top of the IBC at the nose of the trailer due to improper loading. At 2048, ERTS dispatched Kary Environmental. At 0045 on January 29, 2019 the contractor arrived on site and began assessment and cleanup. Impacted rags were placed in a 15-gallon poly drum. The contractor secured the tote and left the site at 0205 EST. The shipper was then contacted about whether to replace the whole tote or just a new gasket then left the site. On February 4, 2019 at 1509 the shipper confirmed with ERTS via e-mail that a new lid/gasket would be shipped and did not require any further need for the contractor to go on site. All waste was staged and left at terminal OS&D for the terminal to manage.

Driver was making a 90 degree slow speed turn at intersection.  The roadway had patches of black ice.  Semi-trailer tires lost traction on the ice covered roadway.  Centrifugal force caused the semi-trailer to slide outward.  The semi-trailer separated from the truck-tractor and slid off of the roadway.  The semi-trailer slid across the snow/ice covered shoulder of the highway.  The semi-trailer slid over a concrete fixture that caused a puncture of one compartment containing diesel fuel.  Approximately 1600 gallons of diesel fuel leaked from the compartment onto the snow/ice covered shoulder.  Clean up crew contained the product in a pool on top of the icy ground.  The product was picked up using suction pump equipment.  The contaminated snow/ice cover was scooped up and disposed of.
column169: Drivers will continue to receive guidance and coaching on driving during adverse weather conditions.

column168: It was reported that on tractor (424571) inside trailer (691297)a super-sack of a regulated product of UN3077. This release was contained to the transport trailer floor with no impact to land, soil, water ways or storm drains. The container was sent to its final destination without further incident.
column169: The driver who accepted this container was retrained on thorough container inspection with an emphasis on container integrity. column168: When the driver closed the dome lid after loading there was a plastic"zip tie" caught between the gasket on the dome lid and the lip of the riser of the cargo tank. This caused an inadequate seal which allowed sulfuric acid to escape from the dome lid and ultimately flow into the crow's nest and out the drain tube. The employee drove for appx. 1 hour and traveled appx. 45 miles. The spill was isolated to a few areas where the driver stopped, turned or ascended or descended an incline. BJ Cecil contacted DPS Duty Office and was put in touch with ADOT(AZ Dept. of Transportation). BJ Cecil coordinated with ADOT and we sent out an in-house clean up crew. BJ Cecil clean up crew neutralized the spill with combination of water, soda ash and de-icing agent.
column169: Additional training has been implemented for all drivers-all drivers have been instructed to maintain adequate "housekeeping" in the crow's nest area of their tankers, specifically to remove and properly discard of old zip-ties from previous loading.

column168: An undeclared hazardous shipment, raft, UN2990 Life Saving Appliance Self Inflating, Class 9, was in commerce to ship from Philadelphia International Airport (PHL) to San Salvador International Airport (SAL).  When the shipment was sent to Kuehne-Nagel (Freight Forward), they became aware that the hazardous shipment did not have the Dangerous Goods (DG) Shippers declaration form.   Stores stock clerk was dealing with multiple shipments when another Aircraft On Ground (AOG) came through and the stock clerk inadvertently forgot to print, complete and sign the DG Shippers declaration for DG raft, UN2990 Life Saving Appliance Self Inflating, Class 9. Kuehne-Nagel informed AA Stores that they have rejected the shipment due to no DG Shippers Declaration form attached and was sending it back to AA Stores.
column169: Employee hazmat shipping access was removed until speaking with the employee regarding this human error to be more cognizant and slow down on processing shipments.

column168: After loading vac truck, employees were clearing the hoses for disconnection. The inlet valve on the truck was closed while the hoses were disconnected. After the employees removed the first section of hose, and were securing it for transport, they noticed material leaking from the end of the hoses still attached to the truck. The entire spill was in containment. The driver quickly grabbed the hose and walked it up the stairs to the tank to stop the flow. The rest of the crew attached the section of hose they had removed, and placed it back in the tank. The employees cleaned up the spill using absorbent pads, and floor dry. The used spill material was placed in drums for disposal. The hoses were cleared into the tank, and secured for transport. The material in the vac truck was shipped to the final destination.
column169: The truck was taken out of service, and pressure tested, which it failed. The inlet valve was found to have a leak. The valve was replaced, and the truck was pressure tested again, which it passed.

On January 21, 2019, at 0038 EST, Chuck Rought of GDS Express Inc contacted ERTS requesting response to an Arc Furnace Dust (UN3077 Environmentally Hazardous Class 9) release of unknown volume due to a multi-vehicle accident.  0105 EST, ERTS contacted Hepaco and requested response. 0120 EST, ERTS spoke with Fire Chief Justin Bailey who reported that the vehicle left the roadway and rolled onto its side releasing 'part' of the load of Arc Furnace Dust to soil and also to a small running stream in an area known to be a Wetland. The Fire Department deployed boom across the stream/creek.  At 0145 EST, ERTS contacted NRC and spoke with MS Rawls, who provided report number 1235666. At 0230 ET, contractors arrived onsite and were unable to confirm at this time the amount released as power lines were down. 0320 EST,The contractor identified diesel fuel, hydraulic oil, and motor oil also released due to the accident. 1742 ET, Contractor indicated that the tarp started to cave in and approximately 400-pounds of product was released to the water. Contractor estimates approximately 1500-pounds of product in total released. 2200 ET contractor loaded the last of the excavated waste to the roll-off box. 2246 ET Sediment and water samples were pulled to be run for cadmium and lead and contractors departed site. On December 22, 2019, the TN DEC stated they were satisfied with the work done. Contractors returned to the site on January 28, 2019, and removed all impacted boom for disposal. Analytics for water came back below the required limit and no further action was requested.

column168: This was a FedEx Padded Pak that exhibited an odor. Upon inspection of the contents it contained a product that said Polyester Resin marine grade on the manufacturer's label. inspection or the contents it contained a product that said Polyester Resin marine grade on the manufacturer's label. A second product said Danger organic peroxide. I contacted the company and requested Safety Data Sheets on both products. Although the owner told me that he would have someone contact me and send the SDS's I did not receive them. I called back a few times leaving voice mail·messages but no one returned my call. It appears that the shipper, Polymer Planet is also the product  manufacturer. After waiting several days for the SDS's I notified our FAA PHI's via email. One product is believed to be UN 1866, Resin Solution, class 3. The other is believed to be an organic peroxide but I could not provide a UN number or proper shipping name without an SDS. The shipment was held pending FAA investigation.

column168: On 1/20/19 at 2208 hours CSX Train A79220 derailed at MP S 626 on the North end of Busch Yard  over Cedar Creek / Broward River located in Jacksonville, FL.  Two tank cars, GBRX 703787 and CBTX 736971 derailed into water.  TILX 199828 derailed onto the bank of the water body.  There were no releases of hazardous materials as a result of this derailment.    Highway 17 (Main Street) in Jacksonville, FL near Busch drive was shut down for approximately 6  hours in which it opened one lane for traffic until the transfers were complete on 1/22/19.   NRC was notified at 2247 (report number 123566); State of Florida Watch Office was notified at 2242 (report number 2019-382); City of Jacksonville was notified at 2239; CHEMTREC was notified at 2316 (report number 2019-01-20-00068).  The shipper point of contact for GBRX 703787 and CBTX 736971 is POET Ethanol Products, Nick Hanna (phone number 316-609-3961; email: nickhanna@poetep.com).  The shipper point of contact for TILX 199828 is Robert Buchek (phone 210-345-2306; email Robert.Buchek@valero.com.    CSX hazardous materials contractors HEPACO, Hulls Environmental, and Marion Environmental  responded to transfer, clean and purge the three railcars.

column168: On 1/28/2019, JBHU 272672 was reported leaking by a JB Hunt driver at BNSF San Bernardino IMF. The waybill lists the cargo as 11 PCS of FAK (Non  Hazardous). In the interest of safety, the unit was placed on hold pending interior inspection and moved to the containment pit.  Interior inspection revealed 11 shrink wrapped palletized Desserthog Battery Packs, stowed down the middle of the container with wood blocking  throughout the container and at the rear for securement. The 10th battery pack from the rear has fallen over to the right side of the container and was  leaking.  Premium Enviornmental was contacted on behalf of JB Hunt and they dispatched Patriot Environmental Services to remediate this load. Patriot did  deem the liquid leaking out of this unit to be UN 2794 Battery Acid (Hazardous). The origin of the leak was the 10th battery pack from the rear that had fallen over from a warped floor. Approximately 1 gallon was contained in the container and less than a gallon was able to reach the ground in the haz pit.  Per Eddie from Patriot the floor was too warped to reload the battery packs into the same container. The battery packs were reloaded into JBHU254679. This incident has been deemed as shipper   s responsibility and all contractor cost from Patriot Enviornmental will be billed directly to JB Hunt Transport.    Cargo and haz pit was remediated by Patriot Enviornmental.

column168: A DAMAGED 406 HIGHWAY TANKER PREVIOUSLY CONTAINING DIESEL WAS WAS OUT-OF-SERVICE AND STAGED (PARKED) IN THE YARD FOR EITHER SCRAPPING OR REPAIRS. THE TANKER HAD BEEN OFFLOADED AT A ROLL-OVER ACCIDENT SITE SEVERAL MONTHS BACK AND THE TANKER WAS REPORTED TO HAVE BEEN EMPTIED ON SITE. WATER MUST HAVE ENTERED INT O THE TOP OF THE TANKER AND SETTLED DOWN INTO THE ALUMINUM OUTLET LINE. WARMER TEMPERATURE MELTED THE WATER ALLOWING IT TO FLOW OUT OF THE CRACKED LINE. AN ESTIMATED 100 GALLONS OF DIESEL STILL REMAINED IN THE COMPARTMENT WHERE IT HAD NOT BEEN COMPLETELY DRAINED AFTER THE ACCIDENT. THE DIESEL WAS ALSO RELEASE FROM THE BROKEN LINE. PILOT THOMAS STAFF IMMEDIATELY DEPLOYED SOFT BOOMS IN THE DRAINAGE SYSTEM THAT FLOWS THROUGH THE SITE AND CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT TO DEPLOY MORE BOOMS AND UTILIZED VACUUM TANKER TO RECOVER THE RELEASED DIESEL FUEL. THE BANKS OF THE WATER WAY, THE IMPACTED GRAVEL IN THE PARKING LOT, AND SOME STANDING VEGETATION IN A WATERWAY OFF SITE WERE TREATED WITH MICROBLAZE. THE BOOMS ARE TO BE LEFT IN PLACE UNTIL NO SHEEN IS OBSERVED IN THE WATERWAY.
column169: ALL DAMAGED TANKERS WILL BE CHECKED UPON DELIVERY BACK TO OUR TERMINAL TO ENSURE THEY HAVE BEEN EMPTIED COMPLETELY.

column168: THE FUEL DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF DIESEL TO THE STORE AND FAILED TO ENSURE THAT HIS DROP GUN WAS PROPERLY LOCKED DOWN ONTO THE RISER OF THE TANK. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF FUEL AND CONTACTED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE COMPANY SAFETY REPRESENTATIVE WHO IN TURN CALLED OUT CURA. CURA WAS ON SITE WITHIN 2 HOURS AND CLEANED UP AN ESTIMATED 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL AS WELL AS A SMALL AMOUNT (1 GALLON) THAT MADE IT INTO A STORM DRAIN BUT DID NOT MIGRATE OUT OF THE CATCH BASIN. FLDEP WAS CONTACTED AND REPORTED ON INCIDENT # 19-342. TOTAL CLEAN UP TIME WAS APPROXIMATELY 4 HOURS.
column169: WE CONDUCTED REMEDIAL TRAINING ON THE DRIVER AND A TRAINER WHERE HE WAS EXPECTED TO DEMONSTRATE THAT HE COULD PROPERLY LOAD AND UNLOAD HIS TRAILER WITHOUT REPEATING THE SAME MISTAKE BEFORE ALLOWING HIM TO RETURN TO HIS NORMAL DUTIES.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While loading, a leak occurred upon disconnecting hose, which resulted in the loss of approximately 20 gallons of epoxy resin. The free product released to the concrete beneath the ISO tank, and sump containment system. OMI was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, OMI cleaned the impacted concrete and utilized a vacuum truck to recover free product from the sump. Free product and rain water were containerized within the sump system and did not migrate off site or threaten to impact state waters. OMI recovered all free product and rain water from the sump system, and site was deemed for closure. Disposal was coordinated per local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

column168: ROUTINE NORMAL PROCESS: TRANSLOADING T DET NP6 FROM RAILCAR TO T-602 (21,100 GALLON CARBON STEEL STORAGE TANK). TRANSFER OF NP9 FROM RAILCAR GATX028882 TO T-602 ACTUALLY WENT TO T-605B (9,000 GALLON CARBON STEEL STORAGE TANK), OVERFLOWING THE TANK INTO DIKE 6.  TRANSFER FROM RAILCAR WAS STARTED AT 3:05 PM DURING FIRST SHIFT. PRODUCT WAS TO BE TRANSFERRED TO STORAGE TANK T-602. SHIFT CHANGE OCCURRED AT 3PM FOR 2ND SHIFT. THE 2ND SHIFT LEAD OPERATOR CHECKED TANK MASTER WHICH INDICATED BY AN ARROW POINTING UPWARD THAT THE PRODUCT WAS GOING INTO THE TANK (T-602). THERE WAS NO METER IN LINE FOR THIS TRANSFER.  AT ABOUT 9:30PM THE LEAD OPERATOR NOTICED THAT THE POUNDS WERE GOING UP VERY SLOWLY AND WENT TO DIKE 6. HE FOUND THAT TANK T-605B WHICH CONTAINED T-DET N 6 WAS OVERFLOWING. HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE INLET VALVES TO THE TANK AND THEN THE PUMP.  NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE SOIL OR WATERWAYS.  CLEAN UP WAS PERFORMED IN HOUSE AND THE WASTE DISPOSAL COSTS ARE TO BE DETERMINED AND WILL BE REPORTED ON A SUPPLEMENT REPORT.

column168: On 01/28/2019 at 2208 ET, it was reported that a cargo release from a 55-gallon metal drum of approximately 30 gallons of UN2319, Terpene Hydrocarbons, Lemon Limonene to the trailer floor and asphalt beneath it.  Clean Harbors personnel arrived on site and confirmed at least two-55 Gallon Steel Drums of UN2319, Terpene Hydrocarbons, Lemon Limonene were found on their sides in the trailer no longer leaking. There are two areas impacted. One under the trailer that measures 10'x10' and another at the end of the trailer that is approximately 8'x3' and impacted the gravel / asphalt of the facility. Clean Harbors personnel inspected the trailer and determined 6 drums were damaged.The team has since overpacked all 6 damaged drums and generated one, 55-gallon steel drum of impacted absorbents.

column168: Original comments:  Driver(van #407044) was returning  to Ground facility with package in a plasticbag to prevent any further spillage of liquid. There where two (2 ) packages inthis shipment.  The other package (#060835682739946) was delivered. It is presumedthat the driver saw the other package had began to leak and was placed in aplastic bag. Upon inspection discovered that many of the closure caps where loose and could be easily unscrewed.  This may be the cause of the spill. The product was handled several times before it arrived at our station. The shipper may need to look into other measures for securing the closures on these items. If something is jarred so often, the caps may tend to loosen over time.  This facilityand driver  had no idea this was the case.  New Comments: Great appreciation to the driver (van #407044) who took all the needed and quickmeasures to contain the spill and to get it back to the facility where it couldbe handled properly by the staff.

column17: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: AT 1415 ON 19 JANUARY 2019 THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF AN ODOR EMANATING FROM AT THE NORTH END OF THE KCS SHREVEPORT, LA RAIL YARD. KCS MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED HAZMAT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND RESPOND. UPON ARRIVAL, THE CONTRACTOR IDENTIFIED THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR AS TANK CAR AZXX 32317 (PLACARDED CLASS 3, UN 1993) WHICH WAS OBSERVED WITH RESIDUE ON THE TANK CAR EXTERIOR. AZXX 32317 WAS CARRYING TURPENTINE WHICH EXHIBITS THE SAME ODOR THAT HAD BEEN REPORTED IN THE YARD. UNDER RED FLAG PROTECTION THE CONTRACTOR BOARDED THE TANK CAR AND DISCOVERED THAT THE MANWAY NOZZLE GASKET WAS DAMAGED. A NEW COMPATIBLE 20" VITON GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE MANWAY SECURED. THE REMAINING TANK CAR CLOSURES WERE CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE, AND THE CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: Original comments:  At 7:42am a package handler radiod management there was a damaged hazmat in thebelly of the trailer he was unloading. QA asked if the package was ormd or an actual hazmat, and both the unload manager and package handler confirmed it was ahazmat. Hazmat was removed from trailer and placed on a pallet especially designated for this type of situation. QA promptly picked hazmat from the unload area,placed in a black bin that had a plastic bag in it, and it was taken to cage 2.Theexterior of the box was partially wet from a leak from the inside to the out butit was determined it was not a spill and the incident did not effect anyone else in the building. Using a box cutter QA sliced through the plastic packingtapethat had sealed the box and inspected the inside. The item was packed withslottedpartitions, but it was wet also due to a leak coming from the cap. Thebox didnot have an tears, rips, punctures, or any signs of being it smashed onany partofits body.  New Comments:

column168: ON JANUARY 29, 2019 SAINT GABRIEL MPF TECHNICIANS WERE CONDUCTING A TRANSFER OF METHANOL FROM A CARRIER TRAILER INTO TEMPORARY METHANOL STORAGE TRAILER (#46679) ON SITE. WHEN THE LINES TOO THE TEMPORARY STORAGE TRAILER WERE BLOWN DOWN SO AS TO ASSURE ALL MATERIAL WAS REMOVED FROM THE LINES, 5 GALLONS OF METHANOL OVERFLOWED OUT OF THE TEMPORARY MENTHOL STORAGE TRAILER AND ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD ON WHICH THE TEMPORARY METHANOL TRAILER SITS. ABSORBENT CLOTH WAS USED TO CONTAIN AND COLLECT THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE TRAILER WAS THEN SECURED. THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL SPILLED WAS CALCULATED BASED ON THE DRUM WEIGHT OF THE COLLECTED MATERIAL. THE NET DRUM WEIGHT IS 41 POUNDS. BASED ON PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATION RESULTS IT IS BELIEVED THE SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF OPERATOR ERROR.  NOTE - NO CODE ON THE INSTRUCTION FITS THIS FAILURE FOR WHAT, HOW AND CAUSE OF FAILURE, SECTION HAS BEEN LEFT BLANK.
column169: THE CORRECTIVE ACTION WILL BE TO ONLY USE 7000GA CAPACITY TRAILERS WHEN OFFLOADING THIS MATERIAL. THE STORAGE TANK (3252-F) IS 5000GA WITH A MAXIMUM OF 4500GA AVAILABLE FOR OFFLOADING. THE STANDARD SHIPMENT OF THIS METHANOL IS 6,000GA. THEREFORE THE SITE WILL ALWAYS NEED A 7000GA TRAILER FOR THIS OFFLOAD.

column17: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: AT 10:37 ON 1/25/2019, THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED BY THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE THAT UTLX 640446 HAD BEEN DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY WHILE CONDUCTING A ROUTINE HAZMAT INSPECTION AT THE KCS ALEXANDRIA, LA RAIL YARD. KCS MOBILIZING A RAILROAD QUALIFIED HAZMAT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND RESPOND. UPON ARRIVAL, THE CONTRACTOR CONFIRMED THE LEAK WITH THE USE OF PH STRIPS. ALL MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE FOUND TO BE TOOL TIGHT; HOWEVER, THE MANWAY LID WAS FOUND TO BE UNEVENLY TIGHTENED SUCH THAT THE LID WAS NOT PROPERLY SEATED, ALLOWING LIQUID TO ESCAPE BETWEEN THE GASKET AND MANWAY LID. A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE MANWAY LID CLOSED. THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE BROUGHT TO AN UPRIGHT POSITION, LUBED AND RENDERED TOOL TIGHT WITH THE USE OF A WRENCH. ALL OTHER TANK CAR CLOSURES WERE CHECKED FOR SECUREMENT, AND NO DEFICIENCIES WERE FOUND. THE VALAVE HOUSING COVER WAS CLOSED AND THE SEAL PIN APPLIED TO SECURE THE VALAVE HOUSING COVER. WITH THE USE OF A LOCOMOTIVE, UTLX 640446 WAS MOVED BACK AND FORTH TO CREATE A HYDRAULIC SURGE WITHIN THE TANK CAR TO TEST LIQUID TIGHTNESS OF THE MANWAY. THE TEST REVEALED THAT THE MANWAY WAS SECURED AND NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED. THE IMPACTED AREAS OF THE TANK CAR WERE DECONTAMINATED AND THE CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION. FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WA ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALVE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS LEAVING THE GULF TERMINAL WITH 8,100 GALLONS OF GASOLINE; AS HE TURNED OUT OF THE TERMINAL THE TRAILER BECAME DETACHED FROM THE TRACTOR STRIKING THE PAVEMENT. NO COMPARTMENTS WERE BREACHED, HOWEVER APPROXIMATELY 5-8 GALLONS OF DIESEL IN THE PIPING UNDER THE TRAILER SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY. CHELSEA FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED AND PUT DOWN SPEED DRY AND STOOD BY WHILE MTI PUMPED OFF THE TRUCK AND COMPLETED THE DELIVERY. TODISCO'S TOWING CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND IMPACTED SPEED DRY AT THE REQUEST OF CHELSEA FIRE AND POLICE. THE TRUCK WAS IMPOUNDED FOR DOT INSPECTION AND THE TRAILER WAS LATER TOWED TO WB HILL FOR REPAIR. THE TRACTOR WAS A DAY RENTAL RENTAL FROM RYDER, WHICH WAS FOUND TO BE HIGHER THAN THE NORMAL TRACTOR USED WITH THE TRAILER, CONTRIBUTING TO THE HIGH HITCH THE DRIVER GOT WHEN HOOKING UP TO THE TRAILER.
column169: AFTER THE ACCIDENT WE PULLED VIDEO FOOTAGE FROM GULF TO DETERMINE THE QUALITY OF PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PERFORMED BY THE DRIVER. AFTER WATCHING IT, WE ENHANCED OUR PTI TRAINING AND ROAD TEST PROCEDURES. WE ALSO HIRED AN INDEPENDENT 3RD PARTY TO DETERMINE IF A MECHANICAL FAILURE PLAYED ANY PART IN THE INCIDENT. WE DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER HAD A HIGH HITCH, SO ALL COMPANY DRIVERS WERE IMMEDIATELY RETRAINED IN COUPLING AND UNCOUPLING PROCEDURES TO INCLUDE VISUAL INSPECTIONS OF LOCKING JAW ENGAGEMENT, MARRYING OF 5TH WHEEL PLATE AND TRAILER, AND PLACEMENT OF HANDLE PRIOR TO ATTEMPTING TUG TEST.

column168: WHILE STAGED ON THE DOCK, ONE CARTON WAS PUNCTURED BY THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR. THE RELEASE WAS PROPERLY MANAGED. THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
column169: RETRAIN THE OPERATOR ON PROPER FORKLIFT PROCEDURES.

column168: DRIVER TRAVELING STRAIGHT ON RANCHO TEHAMA ROAD (NEAREST CROSS STREET IS PASKENTA ROAD). DRIVER TRAVELING AT AN UNSAFE SPEED LEFT THE ROADWAY, ATTEMPTED TO COME BACK ON THE ROADWAY, AND OVER CORRECTED. THIS CAUSED THE BOBTAIL TO SPIN AND SUBSEQUENTLY ROLL ONTO IT'S PASSENGER SIDE. THE PROPANE IN THE HOSE WAS RELEASED, BUT THERE WAS NO LEAK. NO RELEASE MITIGATION NEEDED AS NO LEAK.
column169: DRIVERS CAN BE TRAINED FURTHER ON THE DANGERS AND RISKS ASSOCIATED WITH DRIVING BOBTAILS AT HIGHER SPEEDS THEN RECOMMENDED.

column168: ON/ABOUT 1/8/19 AT APPROX. 0000 HRS. A CORRIGAN OIL TANK VEHICLE WAS NB I-75 APPROACHING THE I-375 INTERCHANGE. AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT THE ROAD CONDITION WAS WET AS IT WAS RAINING. THE DRIVER WAS APPROACHING THE EXIT AT ESTIMATED 55 MPH TO 25 MPH RAMP. THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED AS IT EXITED AT 51C AND SLID TO A STOP ON IT'S PASSENGER SIDE. THE DRIVER EXITED THE VEHICLE AND CONTACTED 911, HIS 24HR. DISPATCHER, AND HIS SUPERVISOR. UPON ARRIVAL EMS TRANSPORTED THE DRIVER TO THE HOSPITAL FOR EVALUATION (DRIVER WAS NOT ADMITTED). DETROIT FIRE DISPATCHED AT 23:57:51, ARRIVED AT 00:02:58. UPON ARRIVAL FIRE FIGHTERS FOUND COMPARTMENT #1 (DIESEL) AND #2 (DIESEL DYED) LEAKING FROM AROUND THE DOME LIDS. FIRE FIGHTERS STOPPED THE LEAK ON #1 BY APPLYING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRESSURE ON THE TOP OF THE DOME LID WITH A PIECE OF ROPE. THEY USED WAX AROUND A 3" SECTION OF #2 TO STOP THE LEAK FROM THE COMPARTMENT. THE DURATION OF THE LEAK WAS APPROXIMATELY 6 MINUTES. COMPARTMENTS 3, 4, AND 5 DID NOT LEAK AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT. CORRIGAN OIL EMPLOYEES ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 0040 HRS. UPON ARRIVAL WE FOUND DRAINS THAT WERE SOUTH OF THE ACCIDENT SCENE HAD BEEN SECURED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL CONTAMINATION. PERSONNEL ADVISED THAT IT HAD STOPPED RAINING SHORTLY AFTER THEIR ARRIVAL. I SPOKE WITH DFD AND DOT PERSONNEL THEY INDICATED THAT THEY HAD IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF STORM SEWER PUMPS TO AVOID TRANSFER OF MATERIAL AWAY FROM THE SCENE. CHARTIER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ARRIVED ON SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 0100 HRS. TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL AND CLEAN UP THE ROADWAY. REMAINING PRODUCTS WERE REMOVED FROM THE TANK VEHICLE AND THE VEHICLE WAS REMOVED FROM THE SCENE. COMPARTMENT #1 LOST A TOTAL OF 55 GALLONS OF DIESEL AND COMPARTMENT #2 LOST 137 GALLONS OF DIESEL DYED. 192 GALLONS TOTAL DIESEL PRODUCT LOST. CHARTIER INSPECTED THE 6 CATCH BASINS IN THE AREA OF THE SPILL.  THE FIRST 3 CONTAINED A FUEL/WATER MIX SO THEY WERE EMPTIED. THE NEXT 3 CATCH BASINS DID NOT CONTAIN ANY FUEL. CHARTIER REMOVED/MANIFESTED (#012716779) 300 GALLONS OF DIESEL/WATER FROM THE SCENE. CHARTIER USED FLOOR DRY AND A MECHANICAL SWEEPER TO REMOVE THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE ROAD SURFACE.
column169: WE HAD STARTED WORKING WITH OUR INSURANCE COMPANY ON A NEW SAFETY INCENTIVE/STRUCTURED DISCIPLINARY PROGRAM FOR OUR DRIVERS PRIOR TO THIS INCIDENT. TH E PROGRAM EMPHASIZED A "DRIVER SCORE CARD" TO DOCUMENT SPEEDING EVENTS THAT WOULD NEGATIVELY IMPACT A DRIVER'S SAFETY BONUS. DRIVER'S WOULD RECEIVE THEIR SCORE CARD ON A MONTHLY BASIS AND BASED ON THEIR PERFORMANCE WOULD RECEIVE A QUARTERLY BONUS. DRIVER'S WHO WERE CITED/WARNED FOR SPEEDING, OPERATING A CMV WHILE USING ANY TELECOMMUNICATION DEVICE, OR FAILING TO WEAR THEIR SEAT BELT WOULD AUTOMATICALLY RECEIVE DISCIPLINARY ACTION (AS NOTED BELOW). DRIVER'S WHO WERE CITED FOR OTHER VIOLATIONS MAY ALSO FACE DISCIPLINARY MEASURES BASED ON A REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT. DISCIPLINARY ACTIONS FOR VIOLATIONS OUTLINED-1ST  OFFENSE-LOSS OF 2 VACATION DAYS, 2ND-LOSS OF 4 DAYS VACATION, 3RD-TERMINATION. THIS WOULD ALSO INCLUDE A LOSS OF THE $500 QUARTERLY BONUS. CORRIGAN OWNERS, MANAGEMENT, AND MEMBERS OF OUR INSURANCE COMPANY MET WITH ALL OF OUR DRIVERS FROM JANUARY 14TH-17TH. WE, ALONG WITH OUR INSURANCE COMPANY, REVIEWED THE INCIDENT INVOLVING OUR FORMER DRIVER (DRIVER TERMINATED DUE TO UNSAFE ACTIONS RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT) AND ROLLED OUT THE REVISED SAFETY INCENTIVE/DISCIPLINARY PROGRAM. WE THOROUGHLY REVIEWED THE INCIDENT, DRIVER SCORE CARDS, AND ADDITIONAL DETAILS OF THE PROGRAM. WE ALSO DISCUSSED POTENTIAL CIVIL AND CRIMINAL PENALTIES FOR NEGLIGENT AND GLOSSY NEGLIGENT OPERATION. ON A DAILY BASIS WE ARE COMMUNICATING WITH OUR DRIVERS ON THEIR SCORE CARD PERFORMANCE. WE PERFORM BI-MONTHLY DRIVER SAFETY MEETINGS TO DISCUSS ADDITIONAL SAFETY CONCERNS/TOPICS, PROCEDURAL CHANGES, AND DRIVER SAFETY CONCERNS. THIS OPEN FORUM MEETING ALLOWS US TO DISCUSS CONTINUAL IMPROVEMENT AND IMPLEMENTATION OF ADDITIONAL BEST PRACTICES.

column168: THE DRIVER HAD RECENTLY TAKEN HIS 30 MINUTE BREAK, HE MAY HAVE BEEN 30 MINUTES INTO HIS DRIVER FOLLOWING HIS BREAK. APPARENTLY HE WAS TRAVELING 60 MPH AND CAME TO A HARSH TURN AND ROLLED OVER. THE LIGHTING IN THE RURAL AREA WAS POOR AND THE TURN MAY HAVE NOT BEEN VISIBLE.  I WAS NOTIFIED BY DPS AT 2230 THAT OUR DRIVER WAS AIRLIFTED TO THE HOSPITAL. HE PROCEEDED TO GIVE US THE CROSS STREETS OF THE ACCIDENT SCENE. I CONTACTED TWO OF MY SUPERVISORS WHO PICKED ME UP AND WE PROCEEDED TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE. WE WERE ABOUT 165 MILES AWAY, IT TOOK US 2 1/2 HOURS TO ARRIVE. DURING OUR DRIVE DOWN I WAS IN TOUCH WITH THE EMERGENCY OPERATIONS PERSONNEL FOR ATASCOSA COUNTY. THEY HAD ALREADY CONTACTED THE CLEAN UP CREW, POLICE, FIRE AND TX DOT WERE ALREADY ON THE SCENE.  THE HEAD OF THE TRAILER HAD BREACHED ABOUT 1.5 FEET DUE TO THE IMPACT FROM ROLLING OVER. MOST OF THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED. BOTH FM 2924 AND FM99 WERE CLOSED, NEITHER ARE CONSIDERED A MAJOR ARTERY ROAD.  THE RELEASE OCCURRED IN A DIRT AREA WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO BE CONTAINED. THE RELEASE WAS NOT CLOSE TO ANY WATER WAYS. THE CLEAN UP CREW ALONG WITH TX DOT TOOK OVER THE EFFORTS AND MANAGEMENT OF THE CLEAN UP.  ATTACHING A COPY OF THE ACCIDENT REPORT AND PHOTO'S OF THE TRAILER.
column169: ENTIRE COMPANY DRIVERS HAVE BEEN THROUGH REFRESHER ROLLOVER TRAINING COURSE ALONG WITH A HAZMAT TRAINING REFRESHER COURSE.

column168: On 1/6/2020, at 1100 ET, ERTS was notified by XPO terminal UBI regarding a cargo release. The handle for the pail is pulling off at the weld. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined terminal personnel could clean the release with the use of appropriate PPE. This release will be containerized into a (1) 10-gallon DM to be staged in OS&D. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.
